    Jeff Bezos's "one-hour rule" is a screen-free morning routine designed to promote menta= l clarity, enhance decision-making, and improve focus by avoiding screens f= or the first hour of the day. Instead of checking phones or emails, h= e engages in activities like reading, spending time with family, or "putter= ing"=E2=80=94a term he uses for slow, intentional activities. = This practice = allows for a calm, deliberate start to the day and is supported by neurosci= ence, which indicates that reducing screen time can boost cognitive functio= n and mental health.
     
    =
    <= span aria-level=3D"2" role=3D"heading" ahbak=3D"true" aria-hidden=3D"true">= What the Rule Entails
    • =
      No Screens:=
      The core of the rul= e is to avoid digital devices like phones and laptops for the first hour of= the day. 
      <= span class=3D"iPjmzb Sorfoc gNGSDf" ahbak=3D"true" aria-hidden=3D"true">
    • = Puttering:
      Bezos use= s this term to describe a slow, intentional period of calm, enjoyable activ= ities. 
      =
    • Activi= ties:
      Examples inclu= de reading, having breakfast with family, reflecting, or going for a walk.<= /span>&= nbsp;
      <= /span>
    Why It's Beneficial
      Improved Decision-Making:
      By avoiding immediate demands and digital= noise, the mind is clearer for making high-impact decisions. 
      =
      =
    • Enhanced Energy and Focus:
      A screen-free morning= allows the mind to be refreshed and energized, leading to better focus thr= oughout the day. 
    • = Better Mental Health:
      Experts suggest that reducing early morning screen use can improve overal= l mental well-being and reduce anxiety. 
      =
  • Neuroscientific Support:
    Neuroscience shows that screens can tri= gger stress-inducing brain waves (delta waves), while activities like light= reading or meditation can promote calming brain waves (alpha waves) and cr= eativity.
